episodes.title: America Hates Poor People
episodes.description:
Poverty is not a choice, it's not the result of laziness, and it's not something that's easy to fix. There are several factors that lead to people needed Food Stamps, including intergenerational poverty, geography, access to education, mental health, physical disability, age, and of course divorce and motherhood, among other things.

We as humans must always help those around us, it's our responsibility as a society to ensure that all within our borders are able to meet basic needs. At some point or another, all of us may find ourselves in need one day.

"Ask not for whom the bell tolls, it tolls for thee." -John Donne

episodes.title: The American Death Cult
episodes.description:
In this video I examine a viral clip of Charlie Kirk defending capital punishment and drawing a sharp moral line between the biblical phrasing “thou shalt not murder” and the broader wording often translated as “thou shalt not kill.” I break down his argument, place it in historical and theological context, and ask what it means for a culture when political rhetoric treats lethal retribution as a moral imperative rather than a last-resort judicial question. 
YouTube
+1

We’ll look at three things: (1) what Kirk actually says in the clip and how those words function as political persuasion, (2) the long history of how religious texts have been read to justify — or to restrain — state violence, and (3) why public calls for revenge matter for civic life and moral imagination. Along the way I reference the biblical contrasts between “kill” and “murder” and why that linguistic distinction has been central to debates about the death penalty and just war theory. 

This is not a partisan takedown — it’s a close read. I’m arguing that language like “you should kill those who kill” is corrosive to democratic norms because it simplifies complex ethical questions into a slogan and normalizes vengeance as civic policy. If you care about how rhetoric shapes behavior and what it teaches the next generation about justice, this is for you. 
YouTube

If this video landed for you, like and subscribe for more cultural analysis. Tell me in the comments: where do we draw the line between lawful punishment and revenge?

episodes.title: Ward Radio slander piece
episodes.description:
There is a reason why most women NEVER speak up about domestic violence: they're afraid. Afraid of retaliation, afraid of being blamed, afraid of not being believed, afraid of what people will think fo them if they know. 

Every day for almost 6 years I have faced these fears and more, and have told my story DESPITE the fear, despite the threats, despite the personal cost of speaking.

I was deeply inspired by Tarana Burke who said that her story WAS the power for change, and sparked the #metoo movement with her book. I decided it was time for a domestic violence me too, #metooathome I called it for a minute. There is so little meida about relational abuse, and my story was horrifying and tragic, but with a happy ending that softened it. Sharing my life has changed the lives of more people than I can keep track of, and it's been amazing to be part of empowering women. But it has NEVER BEEN EASY.

Being attacked by a heavily funded Mormon podcast for sharing the darkest, most terrifying moments of my life, a forced marriage to a stranger and the resulting decades of domestic terrorism, is despicable. These people lack concern, professionalism, and a soul.

My substack article about the day I realized I could not escape abuse:

https://open.substack.com/pub/lifetaketwo/p/the-trad-wife-trap?r=35knav&utm_medium=ios

Video where I read a letter from my ex mom-in-law to Jake telling him to stop abusing me:

episodes.title: Mormon Podcast attack piece
episodes.description:
Today a huge,  generously funded Mormon podcast released a hit piece on me. 

For 24 years, I was the victim of brutal, life threatening domestic violence at the hands of a returned missionary who I was forced by my bishop to marry after he harmed me on our second date. 

I make very little money for sharing my story and shinding a light on domestic violence. I have always shared endless letters and voice recordings, screenshots, diary entries, and other private documents to bring to life the daily world of someone who lives with a dangerous man, and I have been as vulnerable and raw as possible because THINGS NEED TO CHANGE, and the only tool I have to bring any change about IS my lived experience. 

And today, today my life and my very transparent and utterly consistent story was targeted in defense of the Mormon church. 

The tool of victim shaming and targeted defamation is intended to support the patriarchy in question, and was done with no concern at all for me. 
 
I am not a public figure. I don’t have a crew that edits and scripts for me. I am one lone victim with a camera and a ring light dedicated to shining a light on relational abuse, and I am being targeted and harassed by a huge platform that represents the multi hundreds of billions of dollars Mormon church. 

By the way I have read and posted the complete letter from my mom a hundred times at least.  I only hide the personal identifying details. There is NEVER a situation in which it’s okay for a mom to have her daughter and grandchildren kicked out of their home, and my family has harassed and targeted me for years, long before I had an app called tik tok on my phone, simply because I wasn’t Mormon anymore. 

Lastly, I was trafficked. By international definition, forced marriages are human trafficking.
